Owner: CISO / Security Team
Approved By: CTO

1. Purpose
This policy defines how passwords and other authentication factors are created, used, and managed at Kahana to protect access to Kahana Oasis systems and data. It supports SOC 2 requirements for logical access security and password management.

2. Scope
This policy applies to:

All Kahana employees, contractors, and interns.

All systems used to deliver or administer Kahana Oasis: AWS, Supabase, GitHub, CI/CD, Kahana admin tools, Google Workspace, Mixpanel, Stripe, other SaaS.

All types of accounts: user accounts, admin accounts, service accounts, and API keys where passwords or secrets are used.

3. General Requirements
Every user must have a unique account; sharing user IDs or passwords is prohibited.

Passwords and other secrets must never be sent in plain text over email, chat, or tickets.

Users must not reuse their Kahana passwords on any external services.

4. Password Length and Complexity
Kahana follows modern best practices based on SOC 2 and updated NIST guidance, with emphasis on longer passwords/passphrases.

Minimum length:

All interactive user accounts: at least 12 characters.

Administrative and highly privileged accounts: strongly recommended 14+ characters.

Format:

Users are encouraged to use passphrases (multiple random words) that are easy to remember but hard to guess.

Systems may require a mix of character types (upper, lower, numbers, special characters) where technically enforced, but Kahana prioritizes length over forced complexity.

Where a third‑party system enforces stricter complexity (e.g., requiring mixed characters), users must comply with that system’s rules.

5. Password Expiration and Reuse
Kahana does not require periodic password changes solely based on time, in line with updated NIST guidance, unless there is evidence or suspicion of compromise.

Passwords must be changed immediately if:

There is reason to believe a password may have been exposed, phished, or otherwise compromised.

Directed by the Security Team after an incident.

Where systems enforce rotation (e.g., every 60–90 days), users must comply and should create new, unique passwords that have not been used previously for that system.

6. Password Managers
All employees and contractors must use an approved password manager to generate and store passwords for Kahana systems.

Master passwords for password managers must meet or exceed this policy’s length requirements and must be kept strictly confidential.

Password managers must be protected with MFA and, where possible, SSO.

7. Multi‑Factor Authentication (MFA)
MFA is mandatory for:

Cloud infrastructure: AWS consoles.

Source code: GitHub organization.

Kahana Oasis production admin tools and databases.

Identity provider / SSO: Google Workspace (internal—Adam only); Supabase Auth for end-users; Okta for enterprise browser.

Where MFA is available for other critical SaaS tools (ticketing, monitoring, HRIS, finance), it must be enabled.

Acceptable MFA methods include authenticator apps, hardware tokens, or secure push approvals; SMS‑based MFA should be avoided where stronger options are available.

8. Account Lockout and Login Protections
Systems must implement protections against brute‑force and guessing attacks, such as:

Account lockout after a defined number of failed attempts.

Progressive delays or CAPTCHA after repeated failures.

Lockout thresholds and durations should balance security and usability and be documented per system where configurable.

9. Password Creation and Change Procedures
When creating or changing a password, users must:

Choose a unique password that meets length requirements and is not used on any other site or system.

Avoid easily guessable information (names, birthdays, common words, “Kahana123”, etc.).

Let the password manager generate random credentials where possible.

Never write passwords on sticky notes or store them in unencrypted documents.

Where feasible, Kahana should screen new passwords against lists of known breached or commonly used passwords to prevent weak choices.

10. Storage and Transmission of Passwords
Passwords must never be stored in plain text.

Systems managed by Kahana must store password hashes using modern secure algorithms (e.g., bcrypt, Argon2, PBKDF2) with appropriate salting and cost factors.

Passwords must not be transmitted over unsecured channels; all logins must occur over encrypted channels (e.g., HTTPS/TLS).

11. Service Accounts, API Keys, and Secrets
Service accounts and application secrets (API keys, tokens, client secrets) are treated with the same or greater level of protection as passwords.

They must be:

Stored in AWS Secrets Manager (keys accessed securely via Lambda functions).

Access‑controlled on a need‑to‑know basis.

Rotated regularly and promptly upon employee departure or suspected compromise.

Hard‑coding secrets into source code or configuration files in version control is prohibited.

12. Third‑Party and Vendor Systems
When Kahana uses third‑party systems, Kahana users must comply with those systems’ password and MFA requirements, which must be at least as strong as this policy where practical.

Vendor access to Kahana systems must also follow this policy’s requirements, including unique accounts and MFA.

13. Monitoring, Detection, and Response
Authentication logs (successful and failed logins, MFA challenges, password changes) must be collected and monitored for suspicious behavior as defined in the Logging and Monitoring Policy.

Detected anomalies (e.g., multiple failed attempts, logins from unusual geographic locations) must be investigated, and accounts may be locked or require password reset.

Confirmed or suspected password compromises are handled under the Incident Response Plan.

14. Training and Awareness
Security awareness training must include guidance on:

Creating strong passwords/passphrases.

Using password managers.

Recognizing phishing attempts and social engineering.

Training is required for all new hires and at least annually for all staff.

15. Violations and Enforcement
Violations of this policy (e.g., sharing passwords, disabling MFA, using weak or reused passwords) may result in disciplinary action up to and including termination of employment or contracts.

Serious or repeated violations may also be reported to management and, if necessary, to external authorities or customers according to contractual and legal requirements.

16. Exceptions
Any exception to this policy must be documented, risk‑assessed, and approved by the CISO/Security Team.

Exceptions should be time‑limited and include compensating controls.

17. Review and Maintenance
This Password and Authentication Policy is reviewed at least annually or upon significant changes to systems, authentication mechanisms, or regulatory requirements.

Revisions must be approved by the policy owner and senior management and communicated to all affected users.

